2 Functioning of Management Committee (AERWA).

Refer the byelaws under which the Association has been formed and the management committee members will function. 

2.1 Responsibilities 

1.          Serve as the exclusive representative of the association, overseeing and managing the society's affairs.

2.          Organize the general body meetings and the management committee members meetings. 

3.          Provide security arrangement to the society and monitor its effectiveness. 

4.          Maintain common areas by hiring contractors for sweeping and mopping and deploying external vendors for maintenance and general upkeep of the society.

5.          5. Preserve the society's green landscape by engaging a gardeners to water and care for the plants.

6.          Maintain all common equipment or items such as water treatment plant, sewage treatment plant, organic waste composter, lifts, generator sets, transformers, pumps, motors, fire extinguishers, plumbing lines, electrical lines, drainage, rainwater harvesting, and all water tanks. 

7.          Ensure regular checks for lifts, generators, STP etc to stay compliant with government regulatory bodies.

8.          Maintain clubhouse amenities such as swimming pool, gymnasium, aerobics room, indoor games room, party halls, lounge areas, home theatre, spa rooms, billiards, common restrooms and all their equipment.  

9.          Maintain other amenities such as badminton court, cricket pitch, basketball court, amphitheatre and children play area

10.       Maintain the structure and common areas of the society such as internal roads, corridors, compound walls, staircases, terrace and parapet walls, outside walls of the buildings, parking area, machine / electrical rooms and restrooms. 

11.       Facilitate systematic garbage collection from individual flats and coordinate the proper disposal of waste throughout the entire society.

12.       Manage and control the water supply to all blocks, making informed decisions regarding water purchases in the event of a shortfall.

13.       Facilitating bulk services offered by external vendors to society e.g., Ironing, Car Wash, Newspaper, Milk, etc. It will have the right to discontinue service of those vendors providing deficient services after taking majority view of residents. 

14.       Support the cultural committee in coordinating cultural and annual sporting events within our society.

15.       Assist the Social responsible committee in organizing various events and activities at society for the social welfare of residents/workers.

16.       Act as single voice of the society to represent the whole of society members in all matters concerning to the society functioning such as appeal to municipal body, appeal to the government bodies, participation in local area development councils.

17.       Represent the society and all owner in any legal proceeding for any lawsuit which arises for the common area or society wide level.

18.       Promote peaceful co-existence of the residents in the society. 

19.       Maintain confidentiality of the residents’ data and communication. Such data can be revealed only in GBM if the resident is in breach of bye-laws and guidelines, only for the stated purpose. 

 

2.2 Fund Collection 

1.          The association will collect funds through means mandated by the general body such as member contributions, penalties, usage / access charges, administrative charges, renting/leasing of society common area etc. 

2.          General maintenance of the society will be funded through the member contributions towards Maintenance Charges. It covers day-to-day functioning of all staff employed by association.  Maintenance charges comprises of payments to Facilities Management services for Salaries of staff, consumables cost, cost of machinery used, common electricity charges and Annual Maintenance Contracts.

3.          Buying, Maintaining and improving the fixed assets will be funded through member contributions towards Cap-ex Fund (Capital Expenditure/Sinking Fund). It covers plastering, painting, fencing, amenities enhancements, major faults and correction of equipment etc. This fund of the society shall be used for society welfare and capital expenditure (Capex) on society activities as decided and approved by the general body. It shall not be clubbed for general maintenance.

4.          Major reconstructions in the society will be funded through member contributions towards Corpus Fund. It covers major reconstructions, heavy repairs, major structural additions and alterations to buildings as opined by an Architect based on Structural Audits.  It will only be used under existential crisis.

5.          Funds collected by way of move-in / move-out charges, club house charges, open area booking charges, exhibition charges, promotional activity charges, penalty fine collections etc. shall be used to pass on the benefits to all residents. 

6.          The rentals received through leasing of the society common areas for the benefit of the society shall be used to pass on the benefits to all residents directly or indirectly. 

7.          All the rates and computation methodology for member contributions and charges will be based on actual consumption or bills. 

8.          The association shall deposit the society funds in separate current / savings accounts or fixed deposits in the nationalized banks.  

9.          Invoices generated will clearly mention the purpose of collection, due amount, due date, mode of payment, taxes and late payment penalties. Invoices will be sent to email address of all the members of the respective flats registered with the association.  

10.       Non-payment of maintenance dues to society will attract penal action as outlined below: 

a.     Delay beyond due date will incur ₹. 100/- per day as penalty capped at maximum of ₹. 1000/- per month. 

b.     Delay beyond 3 weeks of due date will result in sending a notice to registered email id of the member to clear the dues. Notice sent to registered email id of the member will deemed to have been served after two days of posting. 

c.      Delay beyond 4 weeks of due date will result in auto-disconnection of the services and amenities offered by the association e.g., power backup, garbage collection etc. Such withdrawal will be initiated only after serving notice on the defaulter and giving one week of notice period to clear the dues. 

d.     Delay beyond 5 weeks, during which the resident has neither made any effort to clear the dues partly / fully nor proposed any resolution plan to clear the dues, will cause them to be labelled as wilful defaulter. Association can publish list of wilful defaulters on society notice board.  

e.     Delay beyond 3 months from the date of invoice, will cause association to take up legal recourse against the wilful defaulter.   

f.          In case the collection is quarterly based, one week of additional grace period will be given at each of the stage defined in 10.b through 10.e. 

 

2.3 Decision Making and Vendor Selection 

1.          The management committee members shall meet regularly to take decision on policy matters or other such matters that need AERWA approvals. All decisions shall be made by majority vote only and the minutes of meetings shall be recorded. Any decision by AERWA is valid only if it has been recorded in duly published meeting minutes, unless taken during emergency situation.  

2.          The meeting minutes shall clearly record attendees, agenda items, motions moved, votes polled, decisions made, and follow up actions (if any) with due-dates. 

3.          The association will invite all association members to General Body Meeting every quarter to present the account statement and discuss other matters requiring their approval. Audited account statement will be made available annually. 

4.          The management shall take the approval of the general body for major expenditures. Any unapproved expenditures shall not cross ₹. 50000/- (Rupees Fifty Thousand) per work order and ₹. 150000 (One Lakh Fifty Thousand) per quarter cumulatively. 

5.          For any work order exceeding ₹. 150,000 /- The management committee must gather quotations from different vendors and should select the best vendor beneficial for the society. Such decisions have to be put forward and presented in general body along with facts and figures for transparency and knowledge of all residents

6.          The management committee will act on a resident’s suggestions to check for feasibility and compliance and to procure new services or amenities or assets only if it gets support of majority of residents one per flat. The management will apply its discretion in acting on the suggestion and the same will be communicated to residents. 

 

2.4 Operational Maintenance Services  

1.          A property Manager should be hired to manage day-to-day operations of society support services – Security, Housekeeping, Electrician, Plumber, and Utility Vendor Management.  Property manager will be first point of contact for any society related affairs.

2.          Helpdesk is the key person receiving the complaints, attending, feedback from resident, monitoring the task time and escalation, generating the reports and analysing the complaints.

3.          Security, Electrician/Technician and Plumber are available round the clock. Services of electrician and plumber can be availed for free by residents but they have to bear part replacement cost, if any. 

4.          Duty and responsibility of electrician and plumbers is to take care of any maintenance and upkeep of common area equipment and maintenance of builder provided in-house fittings. Any new installation of repairing of custom installed fittings within the house has to be done by calling external vendors directly by residents.

5.          Resident can log a complaint in MyGate which is preferred mode for faster turnaround time, tracking progress and instant feedback. 

6.          Urgent issues will be attended within 1 working day and other issues will be attended within 2 working days. 

7.          The resident can choose to complaint by following the Escalation Matrix. In case the complaint is not attended to in the stipulated time and no adequate explanation is given, please escalate to next level. The complaint can be escalated to management committee if it’s urgent in nature and needs immediate attention.

8.          The housekeeping and Gardening staff will be working from 9:00 AM to 05:00 PM. On limited occasions of national/state holidays, there working hours/schedule could be changed which will be communicated in advance via Notice to all residents.

9.          Security, Plumbers, STP Operators will work in shifts of 12 hours and shift change timings are 8 AM and 8 PM.

10.       Electricians and technician work in a shift of 8 hours.

11.       Swimming Pool and Pest control vendor works on agreed timings every day to maintain the areas of their scope.

 

3 General Guidelines to Residents  

1.          All the residents should follow the rules outlined in this document, local laws and society bylaws. All residents should show respectful behaviour while interacting with staff such as security guards, supervisors, electricians, plumbers, housekeeping, helpdesk and property manager. Residents should not threaten the staff by hitting them or by verbal abuse. Such actions may attract legal action as deemed fit.

2.          Cooperate with housekeeping, maintenance and security staffs. Treat them with dignity and do not indulge in heated discussions with them. No direct instructions shall be given to them. Kindly drop your suggestion to the management Committee for consideration. 

3.          Owner / Residents shall take full responsibility of their flats, allotted parking, vehicles, family members, and visiting guests. 

4.          Owner / Residents shall keep their contact details up to date in MyGate so that they could be contacted for important communications. 

5.          Owners leasing out the property shall take full responsibility for the conduct of their tenants. Move-in / Move-out guidelines should be followed. 

6.          Flat Owner shall timely settle all dues to the society and the government. The management cannot be held responsible for disconnection in electricity and other services to flat due to nonpayment. 

7.          Permission must be obtained for taking up interior work in the flat by sending an email to AERWA email id (mentioned in the first page of this document). No alterations shall be done that violates the building architecture, structure, design and exterior colour scheme. Interior work is allowed between 9AM to 6PM (except Sunday and Public Holidays) beyond which workers are not allowed to stay inside the premises. Please reach out to AERWA, in exceptional cases.

8.          Flat owners are solely responsible for the safety of workers and staff employed. It’s recommended to do Police verification for the live-in or full-time personal staff. 

9.          Damaging the society property or other resident’s property will not be tolerated and anyone found doing so will be asked to compensate for the loss. 

10.       Keeping flower pots on balcony walls or utility walls for first floor and above flats without any safety grill is not allowed for safety reasons. 

11.       Do not hang the flower pot in the balcony without proper support

12.       Water dripping from the flower pots should not damage the paint of outer walls. It’s required to keep a plate below the flower pots to avoid this damage. In case of any deviation and property loss, owners will be asked to compensate for the loss.

13.       Maintain hygiene and cleanliness in the society. Waste segregation guidelines should be followed and common areas should not be littered or used as personal storage. Smoking, Spitting or Consuming Alcohol in the common areas is prohibited.  

14.       Passive smoking is proven injurious to health. We expect smokers to be considerate of others. They may smoke in their premises but try not to cause any inconvenience to others.  Smoking in the washrooms is prohibited as all flats in the series are connected to same ducts and smoke may enter other flats causing discomfort to neighbours.

15.       Residents should take care of their pets and see to it that they do not create any nuisance to other residents; in case of repetitive complaint necessary fine may be imposed. Pet owners should cleanup any droppings by their pet immediately. Any pet poop left uncleaned in common area will attract penalties.   

16.       10.00 PM to 6.00 AM to be observed as quiet time in the complex which may be relaxed on special occasions only by the permission of AERWA, which will be guided by local authorities and law enforcement agencies.  

17.       Ensure that the audio levels of television sets and audio systems at home are maintained at a level that does not disturb or cause nuisance to others.

18.       Permission of the management must be obtained for organizing community events. The sound levels should be kept low such that it does not create any nuisance to other residents. No loud speakers are allowed beyond 10pm to 6am on any occasions (personal or community functions), unless permitted by Management committee.  

19.       Bursting of crackers within the society is prohibited except pre-approved events. Cracker usage is permitted solely during the cultural event and between 8.00 AM to 10.00 PM. Any exception requires prior approval from AERWA, else a penalty will be imposed on individual / organizers.

20.       Driving speed within the society is limited to 10 KMPH. Do not overspeed, drive rash, honk or play loud music. Any vehicle parked by the owners in parking should have valid parking sticker issued by property manager.

21.       Club house amenities such as gym, aerobics room are open from 5:30 AM to 11 PM. Users are requested to keep the music and other sound volumes in a limit which doesn’t cause nuisance to nearby flats. Windows of gym, aerobics and party hall etc should be kept closed in order to avoid any sound disturbances to nearby flats.

22.       Burning candles, fire crackers, fire such as havan etc is prohibited in the club house as it may cause fire incidents. The organizers of any event which requires above should consult with AERWA and take written approval. Any damage caused by such activities should be borne by the organizers.

23.       Playing with colours in party halls, lounge, swimming pool and any other area of club house amenities is strictly prohibited as it may damage the walls and paint of the premises.

24.       Placing or any idols, religious photos or symbols in club house is strictly prohibited.

25.       Kids shouldn’t enter and play in the gym as it may cause accidents.

26.       Be the eyes and the ears of the society for crime prevention. Report such matters to the Security Supervisor or the Property Manager or the Management. 

27.       Unauthorized door-to-door selling or awareness programs should not be carried out. 

28.       Be considerate of others, especially to the needs of the senior citizens and small children of the society.  

29.       Don’t be over-sensitive about trivial issues for your own and others’ peace of mind. Note that being shared space, residents need to be accommodative of others as well. If you need to complaint, first talk to the other party. Chances are that they may not be even aware of the issue.  

30.       Do not broadcast your personal issues in the group forums without first trying to seek resolution from the malmanagement committee. Be aware that unreasonable demands should not be put on AERWA to resolve an issue in your favour as AERWA will be guided by the society byelaws / guidelines and prevailing laws of the land. 

31.       To safe guard our community’s privacy, usage of drone within the apartment complex is prohibited. Any unauthorized usage of drone will be subject to penalties or cease of the drone or both.

32.       Any harm to society property will be deemed a disruptive act. In the case of accidental damage, residents are responsible for covering the costs incurred by the society. Deliberate damage will be treated seriously by the Management, and residents may face charges amounting to double the repair or replacement expenses, accompanied by a written apology letter to the association.

33.       Any notice put on the notice board should be based on the approval and agreement from management committee. No one should put up a notice-on-Notice board on their own. 

34.       Smoking, chewing gutkha / paan masala / paan in common areas is strictly prohibited.  Non adherence of rule will lead to disciplinary action, and may levy to penalties and fines.

35.       A Resident is allowed to enter premises without making any entry in Register or in app. Visitors accompanying the Residents are also exempted from making any entry in register or App. The Gate Security will have discretion of verifying visitor details.

36.       It is possible that the deployed security guards do not know residency or ownership status. In such case, Security can verify the residency or ownership status and such incoming residents to cooperate with the Security Guards and allow necessary protocol to complete which may include but not limited to:

a.          Seeking identity proof

b.          Seeking proof of residency or ownership by way of call to owners in record or any documentary evidence.

 

4 Security 

1.          All visitors / vehicles are subject to Security Checks as per the Visitor Management process and as per the Security Protocol activated.

2.          Security Team will enforce all the rules of the premises politely but firmly at all times.

3.          Any incident of resident, visitor or vendor misbehaving with security or anyone else in the campus will be handled calmly with the help of the Management members / Property Management Office (PMO).

4.          Pets in common areas must be always leashed. Security can restrict the further mobility of the pet owners with unleashed pets based on their own risk assessment.

5.          Security will follow prescribed SOP for Loud noise and parties after time limit prescribed by PMO and govt. authorities. Noise level to be maintained as per Govt. rules at all times.

6.          Defined Speed Limits and One-Way Routes must be followed within the campus.

7.          Overtaking, honking and high beams is a security risk and will be counted as a violation within premises.

8.          No person of any age should be touched unless any of the following criteria is met

i.        To help a child or any other person in distress or requiring medical assistance ii.           Apprehension/prevention of injury

iii.     Apprehension/prevention of danger, safety (fire, vehicle/cycle accidents, etc.) iv.           Apprehension/prevention of security threat

v. To do any other lawful duty of a citizen

 

9.          Security can take necessary action such as wheel clamping, serving violation notice, collecting penalty etc. from residents who are not following the rules of the premises as per Management SOP but need to inform Property Manager – Management Committee delegates. Security does not have to take permission if the decisions are based on SOP. In case of sensitive decisions security shall involve Property Manager – Management Committee delegates for decision making.

10.       Random checks and unpredictable rotation of Security staff is one aspect of mitigating Security risks. These measures may be followed without prior common knowledge.

11.       Police and Ambulance vehicles are exempted from logging entry / exit in the book at the gate.

 

4.1 Entry for Residents Vehicle 

1.    All residents' vehicles must display a parking sticker; failure to do so will result in the vehicle being treated as a visitor's vehicle, requiring manual entry during each entry/exit. Residents can request a parking sticker by submitting a request to the RWA email. 

2.    Residents with motor vehicles must obtain a parking sticker from the Facility Management Team within one week of moving in. 

3.    Parking stickers should be removed from vehicles when residents move out of Ahad Excellencia as part of the move-out process. 

4.    Residents selling their vehicles must ensure the removal of parking stickers. No new stickers will be issued until proof of removal from the sold vehicle is provided to the management. 

5.    Residents must park their vehicles only in the allotted basement parking slots; incorrectly parked vehicles will have their wheels locked. 

6.    Driveways, sidewalks, entry passages, stairs, and main gates must not be obstructed except for ingress or egress. 

7.    Residents should not park their vehicles in visitor parking for more than 2 hours. 

8.    Guest vehicles entering the society must register through the visitor management app (e.g., my Gate) with the help of security guards at the main gate. These vehicles are allowed in designated visitor parking for a short term, with a maximum limit of one to two days. Parking exceeding this timeframe requires approval from AERWA; otherwise, charges will be applied to the flat owner. 

9.    All residents are urged to use their allocated personal parking space in the basement. 

10.Vehicles parked in residents' parking must have a valid sticker issued by the property manager. 

11.Vehicles should be parked within their assigned limits, and if there's a free space near their parking, permission from AERWA and verbal agreements with nearby parking owners are required. 

12.No vehicles should block driveways or access to electric panels, STP, WTP, or any other society storage rooms. 

13.Parking spaces assigned to flats should only be used for parking vehicles unless approved by AERWA. 

4.2 Entry for Visitors/Guests Vehicle 

1.    Vehicles of visiting guests are permitted inside the complex only if a visitor parking slot is available; parking in any other location is not allowed. 

2.    Visiting guests can park in the vacant parking slot of their resident host only if authorized and accompanied by them. 

3.    Temperature checks and mask usage are mandatory. 

4.    Vehicle entry and exit should be recorded in My Gate at the entry and exit gates. 

5.    5. Visitor vehicles using visitor parking for more than 2 days must obtain permission from the society office.

 

4.3 Entry for Vendor/Staff/Domestic helps

1.          All staff/vendors/domestic helps including maids, drivers, car-washers, dhobis, newspaper vendor, vegetable vendors and other casual workers hired on permanent or temporary basis shall be issued an ID card by the management upon presenting valid statutory proofs.  

2.          Any other casual workers hired for less than a week or where issuance of ID card is not feasible, they will be allowed entry as visitors only after confirmation from respective resident each time with MyGate entry. 

3.          ID cards to temporary workers like carpenters etc. will be issued for fixed-term validity after filling out form as stated in Annexure C by the owners. Any extension required should be requested by the hiring resident to the property manager for approval, before expiry.  

4.          ID cards to regular staff / workers like maids, drivers, car washers, dhobis etc. will be issued without any validity period but they will undergo periodic random checks. 

5.          While entering the Ahad Excellencia premises, staff or vendor should report to security at entry gate, record entry details in the log book and collect their ID card. Entry will be allowed only to valid ID cards holders. Otherwise, entry is allowed as visitor only on the request of the hiring resident. 

6.          While moving around in the Ahad Excellencia premises, staff or vendor are required to present the ID card whenever asked for. 

7.          Any cost to replace the ID cards will be borne by the staff or vendor.  

8.          Temperature check will be done and reinforce the usage of mask.

9.          MyGate shall be updated immediately by the residents while hiring or removing any personal staff from service. 

10.       No vendor/staff is allowed to Basement.

11.       Vendor / Staff / domestic help vehicles cannot be parked in basement (even on request by owner) and should be parked either near entry gate or in visitor parking area. Otherwise, their vehicle’s tyre will be locked.

12.       In case any material given or donated by the residents is being taken by the routine service provider, then such material should be accompanied with the gate pass on paper or mygate which should be submitted to main gate security. The authorization should clearly mention:

i.                Name, contact, apartment number of giver/donor

ii.              ii. Broad description of the items

iii.             iii. Name of the recipient iv. Signatures

 

4.4   Entry for Delivery/Cabs 

1.    All delivery vehicles or cabs may enter Ahad Excellencia premises only upon confirmation by the respective resident. Security personnel at the main gate will seek permission through MyGate.

2.    Records of visitors' entry to and exit from Ahad Excellencia must be logged in either MyGate or the prescribed format in the logbook at the security gate.

3.    Delivery personnel exceeding a reasonable stay time (15-30 minutes) will be scrutinized for compelling reasons for extended stay.

4.    Basement access is not permitted for cabs, autos, or any public transport.

5.    Cabs and delivery vehicles cannot be parked in the basement, even upon the owner's request, and should be parked near the entry gate or in the visitor parking area. Failure to comply may result in the locking of their vehicle's tires.

6.    Public transport and non-resident vehicles are restricted beyond the visitor parking area.

7.    Exceptions are granted in the following cases:

i.               Medical emergencies

ii.             Pick-up and drop-off of physically challenged individuals

iii.            Special cases where people cannot walk due to health issues or emergencies

iv.            Vehicles carrying heavy luggage, especially for air/train travellers or relocation. The resident must accompany the vehicle from the entry.

v.             Packers & Movers or vehicles carrying interior items (four-wheelers only). Security guards will supervise such vehicles up to the block entrance.

vi.            In the above cases, residents must notify the Security Supervisor/Property Manager in advance.

8.    Post and courier delivery personnel must additionally present their official ID cards. In the case of such deliveries, it may not be feasible to inform all residents.

9.    Security will hand-deliver all letters/documents received through registered or speed post according to the decided schedule once per week.

10.Security will not deliver e-commerce couriers collected on behalf of residents. However, they will make an effort to inform residents about the consignment delivery. Residents are responsible for making inquiries and collecting their consignments promptly.

11.Heavy vehicles are not permitted inside the premises between 07:00 PM and 6:00 AM unless approved by the management.

 

5 Housekeeping 

5.1 Waste Segregation and Management 

1.          All residents are required to do the waste segregation at home into dry, wet, medical/sanitary wastes as per the BBMP guidelines. Attached is BBMP guidelines for segregation. 

Wet Waste  

Dry Waste  

Domestic Hazardous Waste  

(Bio and Sanitary Waste)  

Vegetables, Fruits, Fruit peel, Tea powder, Coffee powder, Egg shells, small bones, saw dust,

Flowers, Match sticks, Food, Cereals and other compostable wastes

Plastic: Bags, Dolls, Bottles, Milk

Covers

Paper: Cardboard boxes, Plates, Newspapers, Packing materials.

Metal: Cans, Bottle Caps, Tetra packs

Others: Thermocol, Styrofoam, Batteries, Bulbs, Tube lights, CD's, DVDs, Cassettes etc.

Any item contaminated with body fluids including Diapers, Syringe, Blade,

Buds, Bandages, Sanitary

Pads, Expired medicines, Animal bones, Condoms, etc.

2.          Residents should handover the segregated waste to the housekeeping staff who will be visiting between 08.00AM - 10.00AM every day to collect the waste.  

3.          Housekeeping staff will not ring bell of individual residents to remind them to keep garbage outside. It’s expected from residents to keep the segregated waste in dustbins outside their main doors before the collection period.

4.          Please note, broken glass should not be put in dry waste and should be handed over separately as that might cause an injury to housekeeping staff.

5.          If housekeeping staff does not come to collect waste on any day, please report it to the property manager. 

6.          Residents should not dump the garbage bags in the common area bins unless stated/asked by Facilities Manager/Association to do so in rare cases of HK staff holiday. Garbage bags should be dumped in the bins but they should not be overstuffed.  

7.          No garbage should be kept outside the apartment in lobby and common areas after 10am for it to be lying entire day after the garbage pickup is already done for that day.  

8.          No interior work waste should be left outside the house or in basement. Resident should arrange external vendors to throw the interior waste and debris outside, if same is to be cleaned by AERWA then additional charges would be applied as per actuals.

9.          Pet soiling in common areas should be disposed of as sanitary waste or flushed down the toilet. 

10.       Residents are requested to cooperate with the housekeeping staff in waste segregation and collection process. In case of repeated violations of waste management guidelines, housekeeping will be forced to not pick garbage from erring residence or from the littered common area. Residents are requested to talk to other residents on the floor, so that we don't have this nuisance. 

11.       For any issues, please reach out to the property manager. In case of dispute, decision of the management committee will be binding on the residents.

 

5.2 Sanitation 

1.          Spitting in common area is strictly prohibited within the society premises. 

2.          Do not throw hairs/garbage from the flats to the ground floor or common areas of the society or to some other member’s flat or in the enclosed ducts. 

3.          Food should not be thrown or drained through kitchen sink. The kitchen basins, bathroom sinks, all water drainage points shall be covered by suitable mesh to stop objects going through and prevent water logging in the drainage pipeline.  

4.          All sanitary napkins, condoms, dippers, hair, hair band, cloth shall not be thrown out on to the common areas. Please wrap all such things into a paper box or paper bag or paper cover or biodegradable wrappers and hand over to the garbage collectors. 

5.          Do not flush the following things in toilet to avoid choke-up: sanitary napkins, condoms, diapers. Wrap all such things into a paper box or paper bag or paper cover or biodegradable wrappers with red-cross mark, and dispose them in home dustbins for collection later. 

6.          Flush common area toilets after use and leave toilet seat dry after the usage. Do not urinate on the toilet seat and make it dirty, be a responsible resident.

             

6 Common Area   

6.1 Lift Lobby, Corridors and Parking Area 

1.          Personal things should not be kept in the common lobby. Shoe stand (preferably covered) is acceptable as long as they do not hinder free movement, but they should not cause any movement issues with neighbours, if any issue arises within two neighbours they should talk and solve the matter amicably.

2.          Discarded household items, old furniture, car accessories, explosives, inflammables and garbage should not be dumped in the corridors, lobby and personal parking area. Contact Property Manager to get them disposed safely. 

3.          Misuse of common area to keep personal stuff like cycles, flower pots, dustbins, kids’ prams, etc. is prohibited as it causes hindrance to cleaning of common areas and poses a blocker in view of fire and safety.

4.          Barricading of personal parking space through chains, brickwork, plywood, woodwork etc. is prohibited. 

5.          Vehicles should be parked fully within earmarked area else their vehicle’s tyre will be locked. 

6.          Children are discouraged to play in the basement. They are also not allowed to do cycling or skating in the basement or any other designated parking areas. In case of damage caused by kids, the cost of repair should be collected from the parents.

6.2 Terrace  

1.          The resident should access terrace at their own risk and shall ensure safety of self, friends and family. Neither Management Committee nor any person from facility/security can be held responsible for any kind of incident that may happen because of the lack of security cameras. 

2.          Make sure that no damage is done to any of the installations on terrace like Solar panel, disk antennas etc. Resident is liable to pay damages if any is observed/reported after their terrace usage. 

3.          There should be no permanent cloth drying wires put up on terrace which blocks the walk way of any resident. 

4.          Terrace access is not allowed for running around or any physical activity which causes any discomfort to top floor residents.

5.          Terrace to be used for cooking involving fire is not allowed.

6.          Terrace access is provided only in good faith and any violations of the guidelines will lead to future denial of access.  

7.          Do not leave cigarette buds, empty bottles on terrace.

 

6.3 Driveway 

1.          Maximum speed to drive in Excellencia is 10 Km/Hr. 

2.          Everyone must drive in the directions indicated.  

3.          Drivers should be cautious while turning at the corners. Dome mirrors are provided at corners to see obstructions ahead. 

4.          Drivers should be cautious while reversing. Sound horn before reversing.  

5.          Parents should ensure that children do not cycle / skate / run recklessly on the driveway. Parents must take responsibility of their children’s action during such activities on the driveway. 

6.          Pedestrians have the first right to use the driveway. Vehicles should slow down or stop when seeing any person coming in the way. Pedestrians should not obstruct vehicle movement and give them way. 

7.          Driveways and Parking Area inside the complex should not be used to learn motor vehicle driving, with or without instructor. Driving of motor vehicle by under aged persons and learners inside the complex is prohibited. 

6.4 Kids Play Area 

Kids Play Area is located near Block A5 and B1. Following guidelines shall be observed by the guardians / residents. 

1.          Only children up to the age of 12 years should use the rides. 

2.          Adults should not climb the slides to support their kids as slides and other rides are not meant to carry adult load.  

3.          Adults should not use the kids play area equipment as they are meant for children at all times. 

4.          Residents should not use this area for any other purpose. 

5.          Parents/Guardians should supervise their kids while the fountains in kids play area are operational. 

6.          Parents / Guardians should supervise the movement of their kids. The management shall not be responsible for any injuries or accidents. 

 

6.5 Visitors Parking Area 

Visitors Parking Area is earmarked in front of Blocks G, H and adjacent to the eastern peripheral wall leading to J block for accommodating visitor vehicles. However, visitor parking is not reserved exclusively for parking visitor vehicles as it forms the part of larger common area in the society. Following guidelines have been laid for peaceful usage of this area. 

1.          This area can be utilized for 

a.          Parking visitor vehicles as guided by the Security staff 

b.         Walking, assembly, ingress or egress. 

c.          Setting up stalls or games during any cultural or society events.

d.         Cooking in event of any party or cultural fest  

e.          Community events 

2.          Use of this area for any community or other functions needs prior approval of the management. 

3.          Residents shall not park their vehicles in this area for more than 2 hours, failing which their vehicle’s tyre will be locked. 

 

6.6 Amphitheatre 

Amphitheatre provides an open-air theatre experience and is located adjacent to Block B1. 

1.          It can be utilized for community events like concerts, plays, etc. 

2.          It cannot be used for hosting personal or private events.  

3.          Only snacks and non-alcoholic beverages can be served in this area during the event. 

4.          Programs utilizing the music system and sound amplifier will not be allowed for more than 3 hours & post 10 pm.    

 

6.7 Open Area for Celebrations 

1.          A designated area in open space which is safe and secure can be used for any cultural or religious events for the residents subject to approval by Management committee.

2.          Organizers should submit written or email application to the association stating the purpose of the event along with the program details to get approval at least 15 days prior to the event.  Cultural event committee should be involved in the discussions. Event organizers need to fill out form as stated in Annexure A for event organization.

3.          The allotted open space will be charged based on the space requirement and the number of participants of event and will be limited to closing time of 10 pm.

4.          For any Stalls set up by organizers on such events, association will charge separately per stall or percentage of revenue based on discussions and agreement between association and organizers.

5.          Only non-alcoholic beverages can be served in this area during the event. 

6.          The revenue generated from such occasions will be processed to Association account and will be used for welfare of society. 

7.          Some additional guidelines are mentioned under section 11.1 Organizing Community Events

 

 

7 Clubhouse & Amenities  

Clubhouse and amenities include Gymnasium, Aerobics room, Indoor Games Room, Home theatre, Billiards/Snooker room, Badminton Court, Basketball Court, Cricket Pitch, Swimming Pool, Party Hall, Lounge and Steam, Sauna & Jacuzzi room.   

1.          Clubhouse timings are generally between 5:30 AM to 11:00 PM daily. 

2.          Clubhouse amenities can be availed on first-come-first-served basis. 

3.          Residents are required to fill their entry-exit details in the log book maintained separately for each amenity at the entrance lobby. 

4.          Smoking and consumption of alcohol within the premises of the clubhouse is strictly prohibited. 

5.          Clubhouse users should try to keep the noise to minimum as it is surrounded by other apartments. 

6.          In the event of damage to clubhouse assets, the resident causing it should bear the cost of replacement. 

7.          The management shall not be liable for any items lost, damaged, or stolen from the clubhouse or for any injury, illness, accident or death pertaining to any residents / guests visiting the clubhouse. 

8.          Clubhouse equipment / fixtures / furniture cannot be moved outside the facility for personal use. 

9.          The guests are allowed to use club house amenities provided they are accompanied by the residents. Any amenities which require pay-and-use will be charged to residents and they can be accompanied by their guests.

10.       The management can book the clubhouse facilities for sports, cultural or administrative activities during which use of facilities for personal use may be barred. 

11.       The management reserves the right to change the clubhouse facilities, usage timings and guidelines with prior notice and approval of the general body. 

12.       These guidelines may change based on pandemic situation and government guidelines.

 

7.1 Badminton Court, Basketball Court & Cricket Pitch 

1.          Badminton court, Basketball court & Cricket pitch are open to residents for usage from 06:00 AM to 10:00 PM.

2.          Children under the age of 8 years should have parental supervision. 

3.          Only non-marking shoes are permitted on badminton court. Studded and hard sole shoes are not allowed. 

4.          Players shall not use the court for more than 30 min, if others are waiting in queue.  

5.          Singles game is not allowed when people are waiting in queue to play, unless a match is in progress. 

6.          Players must take responsibility of self as one can sustain injuries while playing.  

7.          Players are advised not to hit the racquets/cricket bats on the court/floor surface or show aggressive behaviour against other users. 

8.          Players are advised to bring their own stuff for playing on these courts.  Management committee will not provide anything from their side.

9.          Maintain cleanliness in the court. Consuming edibles, beverages, or smoking is not allowed.

10.       Kindly instruct the security to switch off lightings before leaving, if you were the last person using above amenities.  

 

7.2 Indoor Games Room 

Indoor Games Room is open to residents from 06:00 AM to 12:00 AM daily. Maintain cleanliness. Consuming edibles, beverages, or smoking is not allowed. 

 

7.2.1 Table Tennis 

1.          Children under the age of 6 years of age are not permitted to use tennis table. Children between 612 years of age can use the table under parental supervision only. 

2.          Players shall not play for more than 30 min, if others are waiting in queue.  

3.          Singles game is not allowed when people are waiting in queue to play, unless game is in progress. 

4.          Any damages to the Tennis Table should be brought to notice of security before start of play. Otherwise, user would be held responsible for the damages. 

5.          Players must take responsibility of self as one can sustain injuries while playing Table Tennis. Also, caution should be applied while playing as the room is shared by other indoor game users.   

6.          Players are advised not to hit the racquets on the table surface or show aggressive behaviour against other users. 

7.          Players are advised to bring their own racquets and ball.   

 

7.2.2 Carom/Chess 

1.          Children below 5 years of age are not permitted to use carom board/Chess. Children between 5-8 years of age can use the board under adult supervision only. 

2.          Players shall not start next new game, if others are waiting in queue.  

3.          Singles game is not allowed when people are waiting in queue to play, unless game is in progress. 

4.          Players are advised to clean the surface of the carom board before start of play with soft dry cloth. Care should be taken to not touch the board (carom and chess boards) with wet hands. 

5.          Any damages to the carom board or chess should be brought to notice of helpdesk/security supervisor before start of play. Otherwise, user would be held responsible for the damages.

 

7.2.3 Foosball 

1.          Children below 5 years of age are not permitted to use Foosball. Children between 5-8 years of age can use the board under adult supervision only. 

2.          Players can collect the ball for foosball table from the helpdesk or security by making an entry in the registration kept at the lobby of club house and the same has to be submitted back after the play.

3.          Players shall not start next new game, if others are waiting in queue.  

4.          Any damages to the foosball should be brought to notice of helpdesk/security supervisor before start of play. Otherwise, user would be held responsible for the damages.

 

7.3 Billiards / Snooker 

1.          Children below 12 years of age are not permitted to use billiards table. 

2.          Players shall not use the Billiards Table for more than 30 min, if others are waiting in queue.            

3.          Any damages to the Billiards Table should be brought to notice of security before start of play. Otherwise, user would be held responsible for the damages. 

4.          Cues without tips may not be used at any time. Keep tips well-chalked. Do not strike the pool table with cue tip. 

5.          Avoid using excessive force to strike billiard balls. Jumping balls is not permitted nor is sitting on the edge of the billiard table. 

6.          Turn on the lights before start playing. Discontinue play in case of power failure or lights are off to prevent damage to the cloth due to miscuing. 

7.          Player using the billiard tables shall return all equipment (balls, cues, etc.) to its proper place. Switch off the AC & lights after use, if you were the last person to use.  

 

7.4 Home Theatre 

1.          Home theatre is allowed for recreational purpose for all residents.

2.          Booking can be made in MyGate for any of the 4 slots available per day (09:00 AM to 12:00 PM, 01:00 PM to 04:00 PM, 05:00 PM to 08:00 PM and 09:30 PM to 12:00 AM).

3.          Serving alcohol, smoking in the venue is not permitted. If found doing so, penalty will be levied.

4.          FMS will check the premises thoroughly after every use and the next users will be allowed entry after noting down any damages. 

5.          Any damages to Recliner sofas or any other appliances will be charged on actuals from the user.

6.          Users shall not move the recliners from their position as that may damage the wooden flooring of the home theatre room.  

7.          It’s expected of residents to leave the home theatre in the same way they would like to see it when they enter. Users leaving the home theatre with clutter all around, will be issued warning and might impact their future bookings if they don’t feel responsible and continue with the same attitude time and again. 

 

7.5 Gymnasium 

1.          Gymnasium is open for usage between 05:30 AM to 11:00 PM daily. 

2.          Users shall take responsibility to use gym facility only if declared medically fit and after understanding the safe usage of gym equipment.  

3.          Children below 6 years of age are not permitted inside the gym. Minors are not permitted to do weight training. 

4.          Users shall wear appropriate clothing and shoes. Do not wear shoes with heels or spikes.  

5.          Do not use an equipment for more than 20 minutes continuously, if anyone is waiting to use. 

6.          Heavy weight training shall be done only after consultation with trained instructor.  

7.          Users are requested to carry a small towel and they should wipe the equipment clean after usage.

8.          Equipment shall be placed back neatly in the designate place after use. 

9.          Keep music at low levels in the music system to avoid any discomfort to the surrounding apartments.

10.       Refrain from yelling, using profanity, banging weights, making loud sounds, carrying eatables, taking selfies / videos inside the gym. 

11.       Users shall inform helpdesk immediately if any equipment is malfunctioning.

12.       User causing the damage to any equipment due to improper handling, shall bear the cost of replacement / repair. 

13.       Kindly switch off air conditioning, lightings and music system and close all windows before leaving, if you were the last person using the gym. 

 

7.6 Aerobics Room 

1.          Aerobics room is open for usage between 05:30 AM to 12:00 AM daily. 

2.          Aerobics room can be used for Warming up, stretching exercise, cooling down and Yoga. 

3.          No equipment from Gymnasium shall be brought into Aerobics room at any time.

4.          Users are requested to carry a small towel for maintaining hygiene so the sweat does not fall on the floor. 

5.          Refrain from yelling, using profanity, making loud sounds, carrying eatables, taking selfies / videos inside the aerobics room. 

6.          Kindly switch off air conditioning, lightings and music system and close all windows before leaving, if you were the last person using the aerobics room. 

7.          Aerobics room can be rented out for the benefit of residents for activities like Yoga coaching, dance training etc. only during odd timings of day when the general usage is low. Such decisions are at the discretion of management committee and prior booking/approval is required for any such activity.

 

7.7 Party Hall/Lounge

1.          Party hall constitutes the main hall area and attached Lounge area.  

2.          Party hall can be booked through MyGate for following timings: 

a.          Full Day Party Hall Reservation:  10:00 AM - 10:00 PM

b.         Half Day Party Hall Reservation: 09:30 AM - 03:30 PM or 04:00 PM – 10:00 PM

c.          Full Day Lounge Reservation: 10:00 AM to 10:00 PM

d.         Half Day Lounge Reservation: 09:30 AM - 03:30 PM or 04:00 PM – 10:00 PM

e.           

3.          Party hall can be booked by the residents for personal events only.  

4.          Party hall can be booked for commercial promotions by the external agencies or the residents for the benefit of residents of Ahad Excellencia. 

5.          Party hall can be availed free of cost only for community events, social welfare events, and non-commercial promotions; provided such events are open to all residents.  

6.          Party hall can be booked for conducting training classes for the benefit of residents. 

7.          Lounge can be utilized free of cost, if the trainer is not charging fees and it’s open to all residents. 

8.          Residents may use the lounge room without a reservation on a non-exclusive basis for small group meetings etc., only when it’s not booked. 

9.          Party hall bookings can be made up to 45 days in advance by residents and 21 days in by external agencies. All bookings are confirmed only upon receipt of prescribed fees within 3 days of booking, where applicable. 

10.       Residents can book and pay through MyGate for their private and commercial events. Bookings and payments for remaining categories shall be done through Property Manager. 

11.       A user can cancel a facility booking before the payment is made. Once after the payment is posted, then only admin owns the access to cancel the booking. Please make a request to property manager. Any refund will be posted as “credit note” to residents account in apartment portal. 

12.       A reservation for the party hall does not include the use of any other recreation facility in the clubhouse, except for the two washrooms located in the ground floor of club house. Party shall be confined to the Party Hall and the Guests should not loiter in other portions of the common area.  

13.       Chairs, Music system and Mics are made available on complimentary basis for use in party hall only. 

14.       Party Hall can be used only for the timings and the purpose for which it has been booked. The management reserves the right to apply its discretion in allowing the use of Party Hall.  

15.       Noise from party hall should not disturb nearby apartments. Party organizers are responsible for the behaviour of their guests. In case of unruly behaviour or misuse of the Party Hall facility, the management reserves the right to terminate the party. 

16.       Serving alcohol and Smoking in the party hall and its vicinity are not permitted. 

17.       Pooja Homa / Havan and Cooking is not allowed inside the party hall.  Placing idols, statues, photos or religious symbols are prohibited.

18.       If required, Visitors parking outside party hall can be used only for food preparation and reheating on extra rental basis after barricading/putting tents and permission by the management. 

19.       Help from society security or housekeeping staff should not be taken while they are on duty. 

20.       For any damage to the party hall, cost will be borne by resident booking the hall based on actuals. 

21.       Decorations strictly shouldn’t be done using strong adhesive tapes or glues which might tamper the wall paint and any damage happening while removing the décor should be borne by the user.

22.       It’s expected from the users booking the party hall to not leaving the party hall with clutter all around and remove the decorations in case of continuous bookings.

23.       Party hall cannot be booked for non-residents or outsiders. However, it can be rented out as a display centre on temporary basis (like furniture exhibition, car launch exhibition etc.). The display centre will be exclusive for residents and outsiders will not be allowed in any case. The revenue generated from such occasions will be processed to Association account and will be used for welfare of society.

24.       If in any case the residents booking clashes with above display event, priority will be given to residents and display event will be asked to shift the dates.

25.       After every use, FMS will check the party hall thoroughly and note down for any damages which will be communicated to the user. 

 

7.8 Swimming Pool

1.          Swimming Pool is open to residents for usage from 06:00 AM to 10:00 PM on all days.  

2.          Swimming Pool maintenance may be carried out regularly on weekdays. You are requested to not use the pool during maintenance period. 

3.          Children under the age of 12 years should always be accompanied and supervised by a responsible adult. Children below 4 years of age are allowed only in the Toddler Pool. Infants are not allowed in the pool. 

4.          Swimming usage is permitted only in proper swim wear (made of Lycra or Nylon). Head cap is mandatory. 

5.          Shower is mandatory before entering the pool for hygiene reasons. Likewise, it is advised to take shower after using the pool as water is chlorinated. 

6.          Swimming accessories to be used shall be washed in shower. Their use may be denied if it causes nuisance to others. 

7.          Do not use the pool if you are not medically fit to swim or if you have skin infections, open wounds or other contagious diseases. 

8.          Do not enter the pool after consuming alcohol for your own safety. 

9.          Diving is not permitted due to insufficient depth. Use only the railing steps to descend into the pool. 

10.       Maintain cleanliness in the Swimming Pool premises. Consuming edibles, beverages or smoking is not allowed. 

11.       No private party is allowed in the pool premises.  

12.       Do not run, only walk on the pool deck. Parents shall monitor the movement of their children while in the Swimming Pool premises. 

13.       The management shall not be responsible for any accidents / mishaps / losses which may occur in the Swimming Pool. 

 

7.9 Steam, Sauna & Jacuzzi Room

The guidelines for usage of Steam, Sauna and Jacuzzi will be put forth only after discussion with professionals on this facility. Until then your cooperation is requested.

 

8 Use of Elevators / Lifts   

1.          Observe the safety precautions highlighted inside the lift. 

2.          Do not overload lift beyond the rated capacity. 

3.          Do not enter or exit the lift until it stops completely. 

4.          Do not place your hand or foot between lift doors to prevent it from closing. 

5.          Do not delay other passengers by holding the lift for prolong periods. 

6.          Be vigilant while entering and exiting as lift floor may not be aligned with building floor. 

7.          Do not press lift buttons unnecessarily neither allow children to play with them. 

8.          Do not draw graffiti on walls or litter inside the lifts. Smoking is prohibited. 

9.          Do not use lifts in case of emergencies like fire and earthquake. 

10.       Do not panic if the elevator stops in between floors or if it wobbles. You are safe inside the lift. Keep the alarm button pressed and wait for help.  

11.       In case of getting stuck in lift due to power issue, do not panic. Lift doors will open on next floor within a minute, if you get stuck for longer than a minute then press the bell button in lift and use the call button to speak to someone available on ground floor for help.

12.       Children under 12 years of age should not use the lift alone unless accompanied by an adult. 

13.       Children should be instructed not to play around the elevator. 

14.       Instruct your children about lift usage safety guidelines. 

15.       Packages or household items of only prescribed size (6ft x 3ft x 2ft) can be carried through lift. Do not carry items which are heavier than lift capacity or which exceed the above stated size. 

16.       Kid’s cycle / strollers / prams can be carried in lift. Adult cycles (i.e., length greater than 3.5ft) should not be carried in the lift and should be parked in basement. 

17.       When coming down, whenever possible, use the staircase. This will do well to your health as well as help in keeping our power consumption low.   

 

9 Move-In / Move-Out  

Following guidelines cover the residents move-in / move-out from Ahad Excellencia due to sale of the flat or due to letting the property for tenancy. 

 

9.1 Move-in and Move-out 

1.          The owner/tenant moving-in as resident or moving-out shall request Gate Pass or NOC by applying in Move-in/Move-out form as stated in Annexure B before the move in or move out in advance.

2.          Parking stickers can be requested with the same Move-in/Move-out form. 

3.          No items should be stored/left in common areas.

4.          The Move-in and Move-out charges are kept at ₹. 1000/- each subject to change in future. First Move-in from the date of purchase of the flat will be without any Move-in charges. During resale, Move-in, Move-out charges will be incurred.

5.          Move-out has to be notified to association 3 days prior to actual date to check all liabilities and dues for the apartment. Any delay from resident’s side will delay the process of issuing the Gate Pass and NOC.

6.          There should be no damage to common areas lifts, walls, lobbies, electrical items, etc. while move in or move-out.

7.          It’s not recommended to use lift for such stuffs which might cause damage. Security deployed will take care for any damage happened and will inform property manager accordingly.

8.          All applications shall be made to society office during working hours. 

9.          Shifting of material during move-in / move-out is allowed only between 08:00 AM – 07:00 PM. Security is instructed to not allow any material movement unless expressly permitted by the management. 

10.       The Main Gate security to ascertain if any damage to common infrastructure has happened, the same be reported to the Property Management Office. In such case, the vehicle to be let out only after due written approval from the Property Management Office

11.       Tenants moving-in needs to fill in move-in/move-out form, submit their Rent agreement copy, ID proof and based on the details parking sticker will be issues and MyGate access will be provided within 1 week time period.

9.2 Letting the Property 

1.          Apartment can be let only for private residential purpose. 

2.          Apartment can be let either to family or to singles. However, in case of singles, a maximum 2 person for 1BHK, 4 people for 2 BHK and 6 people for 3BHK are allowed per flat. 

3.          Both owner and tenants should abide by the rules and regulations of the society. Owner will be finally held accountable for any violation to the society guidelines.  

         

9.3 Transfer or Sale of Property 

1.          Apartment can be transferred only for private residential purpose. 

2.          Transferor shall obtain a “No Objection Certificate” (NOC) from the association before executing sale of an apartment. NOC will be issued only after all dues to the association are settled. 

3.          Transferee is advised to seek the above-mentioned NOC from seller before executing sale or conveyance deed. In its absence, transferee is liable to settle all pending dues on the said apartment with the association. This being a standard legal practice, ignorance to the herein stated guidelines is not an excuse. 

4.          It is the responsibility of the transferee to seek and understand the society guidelines before entering into any agreement with transferor. Ignorance to the society guidelines will not be an excuse in case of any dispute with association. 

5.          Applicable fees shall be paid to the association by new party moving in the apartment complex to gain the membership of General body after filling out a form as stated in Annexure D.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

10 Pet Ownership  

Recognizing that pets play an integral role in the lives of some residents, we acknowledge that not everyone shares the same sentiments. To ensure the well-being of all residents and their animal companions, the following guidelines have been established:

1.    Pet owners are required to take responsibility for their pets' behavior, ensuring that they do not cause discomfort or inconvenience to other residents.

2.    Mandatory registration of pets with BBMP is essential. Pet owners must adhere to municipal guidelines for the proper care of their animal companions and provide a copy of the pet registration to the association.

3.    Pets should be kept clean at all times, with up-to-date vaccinations and immunizations. The management reserves the right to inspect vaccination records.

4.    Pets must be kept on a leash and under the control of their owner when outside their apartment. The designated garden space near OWC is the only area where pet owners can unleash and play with their pets.

5.    Pets are permitted in common areas only when on a leash.

6.    Pet owners are responsible for cleaning up after their pets, ensuring proper sanitation and training them not to defecate in open areas within the complex. Pet waste disposal should adhere to waste management guidelines.

7.    Pet parents are expected to carry tools for collecting their pet's excreta. If tools are not available, waste should be collected within 30 minutes.

8.    Pet parents are encouraged to carry water to sanitize any common area where their pet urinates.

9.    Any attacks by pets on people or other pets will be addressed seriously by the association. However, parties involved are encouraged to attempt amicable resolution before involving the association.

10.Non-pet owners should refrain from teasing, screaming, or chasing pets and educate their children accordingly.

11.Non-pet owners are encouraged to report instances of perceived negligence by pet parents.

12.Depending on the severity and recurrence of offenses, the association may take extreme measures such as restricting an errant pet from common areas, mandating muzzling, and imposing fines on the pet owner. 

 

 

 

11 Cultural and Sports Events   

11.1 Organizing Community Events 

1.          The management shall assist organizing of social, cultural and sports events within the society premises to increase harmony among the residents.  

2.          Any event shall be organized only after seeking written approval from the management committee via email. Details such as timings, venue, and activities planned, etc. should be provided for approval before the event is publicized.  Event organizers need to fill out form as stated in Annexure A for event organization.

3.          The management committee will provide its decision after review and may put additional conditions / restrictions to conduct the event in the best interest of the society. Some events may be disallowed on safety and security grounds. 

4.          The association will fund only 4 events during a given calendar year – Two National Events (Republic Day and Independence Day) and One State Event (Kannada Rajyotsava) and One Annual Day. Organizers may seek voluntary contributions from the society or raise fund through other means for all other events. 

5.          Any brand promotion, flea markets, food counters etc. set-up during a cultural event will incur a fee for the usage of common area. At present, this is at 20% of the revenue generate from these sources. However, AERWA reserves the rights to determine the fee, and is subject to change based on the market conditions.

6.          The sound levels should be kept under permissible limits and should not cause discomfort to residents staying in their flats. Upon complaints from the residents AERWA will reserve the right to ask the organizers to reduce the volume, if organizers do not follow the guidelines, then electric connection to the speakers will be disconnected. Residents are requested to turn the volume low after 9 PM to minimize inconvenience to other residents. No loud speakers are allowed beyond 10 PM. 

7.          Entry shall be open to all but restricted to only the residents and their guests. 

 

11.2 Cultural, Social Welfare and Sports Committees 

1.          Three POCs will be identified from AERWA to bridge and support between AERWA and Organizing Committees. Residents are required to reach out to them for any support from AERWA during celebration and also add them to Your respective cultural groups for timely support.

2.          Official Celebration: AERWA will officially commemorate three significant events each year at Ahad Excellencia- Independence Day, Republic Day, and Kannada Rajyotsava. AERWA has set a maximum expenditure cap to support these festival, and it is subject to change based on the market condition.  . Volunteers are encouraged to participate and raise additional funds as required to meet the overall budget.

3.          Resident-Organized Festivals & Calendar: Residents are welcome to celebrate individual or group festivals within the community. In such cases, organisers are requested to notify AERWA with event details and dates well in advance. This will allow RWA to create a cultural calendar.

4.          Facility Usage: Events registered with AERWA will be granted complimentary access to the Club House (Lounge and Party Hall) for one day. Any additional requirements will be subject to the amenity booking protocol.

5.          Date Changes: If there is a need to change the event date, please communicate this to AERWA via email at least one month in advance to allow for proper booking arrangements, subject to the availability of the Party Hall or Lounge.

6.          Transparency in Contributions: In cases of voluntary contributions from residents, it is mandatory to disclose income and expenditure reports in front of the contributing residents to maintain transparency.

7.          Sponsorship Payments: All payments from sponsorships, flea markets, brand promotions, etc., directed to the AERWA bank account will be disbursed in full to the Volunteer Committee within the same month.

8.          Association Share: Payments from these sources will incur a 20% share for the RWA for the usage of Ahad Excellencia common areas.

9.          Reporting and Invoicing: The Volunteer Committee should inform AERWA of the amount received from brand promotions, flea markets, etc., via email. Subsequently, AERWA will generate an invoice for the 20% share, which will be billed to the Flat Number of the SPOC for the Volunteer Committee, and can be paid via Mygate.

10.       In case of the event exceeds the established Panchayat or local governing body guidelines, the organizing committee must obtain approval from the relevant authority, with AERWA facilitating the coordination.

11.       Respect your neighbours’ privacy and cultural customs, which may affect noise levels, shared spaces, and attire.

12.       If cultural conflicts arise, approach them with an open and respectful attitude, seeking to understand and find common ground. AERWA will always support peaceful resolution.

13.       Any damages to the Ahad property during celebration will be borne by Organising committee.

14.       Manhandling or violation or any kind of violence during celebration... organising committee will be fully responsible and accountable for same.

15.       Usage of Crackers and Loud speakers are restricted to and between 8.00 AM to 10.00 PM. Any exception requires prior approval from AERWA, else a penalty will be imposed on individual / organizers.

16.       Cultural event requiring video coverage using drone, requires prior approval from RWA. A detailed email to be sent to AERWA mailbox, explaining the purpose, timing etc.

17.       In the event of usage of drone within the apartment complex, users must provide a written assurance affirming responsibility for any unintended information is captured and disclosed publicly via drone. Unauthorized usage of drone will be subject to penalties.

 

12 Water Conservation and Management  

The society sources its water through bore well or tankers (occasionally, when bore well motors are faulty or water collection from borewell is lower than the requirements). Management will be looking to regulate water supply in the society through water meters to monitor the water consumption and collect the charges accordingly So, to minimize wastage of water during daytime and enjoy 24x7 water supply following recommendations must be observed by all: 

1.          Washing machine should be used only when full load of laundry is available. 

2.          Aerators in the taps should not be removed. 

3.          Water saving aerator should be fitted in at least the taps in utility and kitchen sink. 

4.          Residents should train their maids and drivers to use water preciously. 

5.          Water pressure in taps should not be kept at full and flow should be regulated for optimum use. 

6.          If any tap is found open in a locked flat, that individual shall be fined as per prescribed penalty. 

7.          Water discarded through water filters should be stored and used for washing utensils, watering plants, mopping the floor etc. 

 

13 Alterations, Installations and Repair  

13.1 Building Maintenance and Repair  

1.          Any building is susceptible to natural calamities and weather. Hence, some kind of problem is anticipated to arise over time. Residents can register their complaints through MyGate.  

2.          The association shall not bear costs of repair and replacing the fittings, fixtures, pipes, walls and other such items that constitute the resident’s apartment and solely owned by them. 

3.          The association is not responsible for the rectification of any electrical lines, telephone lines, solar heater and electrical appliances owned by the resident.  This is also applicable to MCB panel of flats that are installed in common electrical rooms. 

4.          Whenever the repair work is confined to the flats, the incurring expenses are to be borne only by the flat owners.  

5.          If the defect also affects the adjacent flats, then all the affected members will share the cost of repairing work proportionate to the costs involved in their respective flats. In case the repair work involves the common areas and building structure, the association will also share the costs proportionately. 

6.          For structural defects in their flats, individual members are requested to personally register a complaint to the builder explaining the severity of the issue. The builder contact details can be collected from the society office.  

7.          The management committee shall also track the work progress by means of feedback received by members registered against their complaints and will get involved in case the repair is involving the building structure or common areas. 

8.          Members are free to appoint a civil contractor other than one suggested by the management, only for non-structural issues, but will need to take prior approval from the management committee. 

9.          Decision of the management committee shall be binding in case of dispute between residents. 

 

13.2                   Air Conditions (AC) Installation.  

1.          Designated Locations: AC installations should be carried out within your residential unit, using the allocated space provided by the builder.

2.          Prohibition: According to section 10.1 & 10.2 of the Deed of Declaration, it is prohibited to use common walls for personal purposes, including the installation of equipment, machinery, and electrical or electronic devices.

3.          Aesthetic Considerations: The exterior appearance of our community is essential. Installing AC units on common walls detracts from the overall aesthetics. Therefore, it is the responsibility of each resident to maintain a uniform and visually pleasing appearance of the building.

4.          Noise Control: Installing AC units on common walls or roofs can result in noise disturbances for fellow residents.

5.          Structural Integrity: Installing units on common walls or roofs poses risks to the structural integrity of the building.

6.          Safety and Liability: Terraces are common areas accessible to all residents. Installing electrical units there may lead to electrical mishaps during rainy days, potentially harming residents.

 

13.3                  Apartment Maintenance and Repair / Interior Work 

1.          The flat owners shall always take prior approvals from the management committee for any alterations that are made inside their flats, and also submit the necessary plan for such alterations. If the work plan submitted is found to be in violation of building plan, the society has the right to stop the work.  

2.          New owners taking handover from builder/landlord should satisfy themselves on working condition of all wirings, plumbing, intercom lines, TV cable lines etc. It is builder/landlord responsibility to rectify any defects so identified for which residents should follow-up with them.  

3.          Any tampering of the building structure – that include changing wall positions, pillars and beams is prohibited. 

4.          Alterations shall not cause changes to the external elevations of the building. No work shall be undertaken that requires additions/deletions/modifications/changes in position etc. of the windows, doors, overall footprints of the apartment, internal layout of the apartment, balconies, architectural features, fabrication works (grills, balcony railings, etc.) and external painting other than what is approved by the association. Any violations so found shall be fixed by the owner within 15 days of receiving notice. Failing this, the management will take up the work to fix the violation and charge the owner double the cost incurred by the society. 

5.          The alteration or interior work shall be undertaken between 09.00 AM to 6.00 PM only, except on Sunday and public holidays. 

6.          The civil work and all other installations like electrical wiring, plumbing (pipeline alterations) etc. 

must be done by qualified contractors or who have reputed background. These are not covered in electrician/plumbing services offered by association. 

7.          Any cabling for DTH / Internet / telephone etc. has to be done through internal ducts provided in each block. Extending it from outside or common areas is strictly not allowed. 

8.          The flat owner is solely responsible for the safety of the workers hired by them as well as for the safety of the people moving near the flat. Adequate measures should be taken to ensure safety. 

9.          Workers hired shall abide by the conditions listed in the section 4.3 Entry to Vendor or Staff.

10.       Flats owners will be responsible to compensate or rectify all problems faced by adjacent flats and/or the common areas due to the alteration work. 

11.       The generator back up points provided in common area must not be used for other than the intended purpose. 

12.       The owner should get all the construction debris and waste disposed of through their contractor. They should not be disposed of in society common areas. 

13.       The association reserves the right to periodically inspect the repair / renovation work by giving advance notice to owner.

 Please refer to below information about how to communicate with AERWA, it’s staff and escalation matrix

14.1 Escalation Matrix

6.          For any issue/feedback related to Property Manager, please reach out to Management committee via email.

 14.2 Communication from association  

1.    Mygate will only be the preferred mode of sending communications from association side.

3.    The telegram groups will used to share information pertaining to General Awareness/ /Information/Knowledge Sharing and which does not require Mygate notice.

4.    The General body meeting will be mode of communication to highlight the works achieved, financials, issues pending, works in progress and for passing major resolutions.
